diacy experience I prefer.\n- The Cohesive artist album (concise 3–5 minute, riff‑forward rock): this candidate explicitly matches the core of my taste — concise 3–5 minute songs, riff‑forward arrangements, midrange‑forward crunchy guitars, tight driving drums, gravelly roomy lead vocals up front, warm muscular low‑mids, analog transient‑preserving mastering, and crucially a cohesive artist album rather than a compilation. It also specifies no glossy brick‑wall compression, which aligns directly with my aversion to heavy limiting and desire for tactile attack, clear instrument separation and roominess.\n3) Why I choose the cohesive artist album and reject the greatest‑hits collection\n- Choice rationale: The cohesive artist album is a far closer match to the detailed, specific attributes I care about. It checks the boxes that define my listening priorities: song length (concise 3–5 minutes), arrangement focus (riff‑driven, tight rhythm section), tonal balance (midrange‑forward crunchy guitars, warm muscular low‑mids), vocal character (gravelly, roomy lead up front), and mastering philosophy (analog/transient‑preserving and explicitly not brick‑wall compressed). Those combined elements reproduce the late‑70s/early‑80s hard‑rock immediacy and live feel I seek, and the fact it is a cohesive artist album means sequencing and album flow will support that live‑in‑the‑room experience rather than breaking it up.\n- Rejection of the Greatest Hits Collection: although it shares some technical strengths (warm analog tone, preserved micro‑dynamics, tasteful remastering), its greatest‑hits nature and emphasis on intimate, forward lead vocals plus multi‑tracked harmonies conflict with two important dislikes: a tendency toward radio‑polished, harmony‑stacked fronts and non‑cohesive sequencing. Those traits dilute the raw, riff‑forward, gravelly‑fronted hard‑rock character I favor. In short, the Greatest Hits offers some attractive mastering choices but likely fails to deliver the 